          "body": "Verse 6 is the chapter's theological engine. The LORD caused the Aramean army to hear 'a sound of chariots and a sound of horses, even the sound of a great army.' No army is dispatched, no prophet appears in the Aramean camp, no angel strikes anyone. God reroutes the Aramean army through their own ears and their own fear. The explanation they construct (7:6) — that Israel has hired the Hittites and the Egyptians — is plausible geopolitically (both nations had provided military assistance to regional powers before) and entirely wrong. Panic converts a besieging army into a fleeing one, and a besieged city's margin-dwellers walk into a fully provisioned military encampment. The method matters theologically: God accomplishes a complete military reversal without any of Israel's military assets, through the perception of people on the wrong side, using the legs of four dying men as His delivery vehicle. Calvin's principle of divine sovereignty operating through secondary causes is nowhere more surgically illustrated in the historical books."
