          "title": "The ethics of good news — silence named as sin",
          "body": "The chapter's ethical pivot is 7:9. The lepers, having eaten and begun hoarding silver and gold and clothing, pause and name what they are doing as morally wrong: 'we are not doing right. This day is a day of good news, but we are keeping silent.' The Hebrew word besvorah — good news, tidings of victory — carries the full weight of its cognate significance. This is not merely information they are withholding; it is news that would end a famine, save a city, and fulfill a prophecy. Their silence is not passive; it is an active retention of what belongs to others. The lepers recognize that punishment (*avon matsa*, their sin overtaking them) awaits continued silence. They do not need a command from Elisha or a rebuke from the king; their own moral reasoning brings them back. The sequence — discover, hoard, self-correct, report — is a compressed portrait of how conscience functions even in those the community has written off. Their self-correction in 7:9 is among the most theologically precise ethical moments in the historical books."
