          "title": "The report chain and the king's unbelief",
          "body": "Once the lepers report to the gatekeepers (7:10), a chain of nagad runs upward through Samaria's social hierarchy: gatekeepers to the king's household (7:11), king to his servants (7:12), servants proposing a reconnaissance mission (7:13-14), scouts to the king (7:15), and finally the people to the plundering of the camp (7:16). What is striking is the king's response at 7:12: he does not believe the report. He constructs a conspiracy theory — the Arameans have left the camp as a trap, lying in ambush in the field. The king who dismissed Elisha's word in chapter 6 (6:31-33) is now the last person in the city to be persuaded by a report that confirms it. His servant's proposal in 7:13 is bleakly pragmatic: the horses are going to die anyway, the men are going to die anyway — send them and see. The scouts who verify the abandoned road all the way to the Jordan are not prophets or heroes; they are reconnaissance men following a desperate servant's suggestion. The word of the LORD fulfills itself despite the king, through those closest to the city's margin."
